This came from the estate of the late Brigadier General Walter McIlhenny, USMC who was a Navy Cross recipient and known to appreciate good guns and the great outdoors. He was the President of Tabasco until his passing in 1985.Local, FTF deal only, please.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Cimarron M1911 .45ACP
postcontent: Up for grabs here is a like-new Cimmaron M1911 in .45 ACP!This is a modern replica of the original M1911 disign used in both World Wars that was designed by Cimmaron for the Cowboy Action Shooting scene.  It's a nice shooting piece, reliable, accurate, and gets decent reviews from the gun press.   It's especially good if you're a WW1 or WW2 reenactor or into Cowboy Action shooting.  But it's also just a very nice entry level .45.  I've put perhap 300 rounds through it, so my loss is your gain!  I bought it with a mind to get back into reenacting, but plans have changed.  Again, the gun is in like-new condition.  The spot you see in the photo is shine from oil, not a blemish on the finish. With the pistol is included the original plastic carrying case and two after-market 8 round magazines.  I'll also throw in 1 box of 50 rounds of .45 ACP as this is the only pistol I currently own in that caliber and will have no need for it once this is moves. (I'm a 9mm guy...)   I'm asking a firm $375 for the handgun.  Given that the MSRP for these is over $500 and average street price is about $450, this is a great deal.  Act quick before this one gets away from you.  I prefer a cash sale, but will consider a limited number of trades.  I'm in the market for a smaller frame .357 Magnum revolver such as a Ruger SP01 or a Taurus 605 as a alternate carry piece.  Thus if you have something along those lines we might be able to work out a deal.  Obviously a low value trade such as a used Taurus will have to have it's value  made up for either in cash or other items.  But let me know if you have an offer that falls along those lines.   The above are just common examples.  I'm open to other small frame .357s as well.Now the boring part...By replying to this add you afirm that you are able to legally purchase a handgun in the state of Texas.  I reserve the right to refuse sale to any prospective buyer for any reason.  If I don't like the look of you, I walk.  Given the extra expense and hassle of FFL transfers, local pickup only, please.  I have had good luck in the past conducting transactions in public places such as the parking lot of a known gun retailer.  (it's safer for all concerned and locals are not likely to be alarmed by the sight of firearms due to the location.)   First come first serve and all sales/trades are final.  Text me at REDACTED if you are interested in a purchase or have a trade proposal.  I work early hours, so will be unlikley to reply to any text before tommorrow (9/5), but will reply as soon as possible.
